{"award_age":70.0,"bio_image":"full\/4c29da3cf993770373b45075ff60903613c77c1c.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"Austria","date_of_birth":"1903-11-07T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1989-02-27T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/a\/a1\/Konrad_Lorenz.JPG\/220px-Konrad_Lorenz.JPG"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Konrad_Lorenz","mini_bio":"<p><b>Konrad Zacharias Lorenz<\/b> (7 November 1903 \u2013 27 February 1989) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Austria\" title=\"Austria\">Austrian<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Zoology\" title=\"Zoology\">zoologist<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ethology\" title=\"Ethology\">ethologist<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ornithologist\" title=\"Ornithologist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">ornithologist<\/a>. He shared the 1973 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nikolaas_Tinbergen\" title=\"Nikolaas Tinbergen\">Nikolaas Tinbergen<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Karl_von_Frisch\" title=\"Karl von Frisch\">Karl von Frisch<\/a>. He is often regarded as one of the founders of modern <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ethology\" title=\"Ethology\">ethology<\/a>, developing an approach that began with an earlier generation, including his teacher <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Oskar_Heinroth\" title=\"Oskar Heinroth\">Oskar Heinroth<\/a>.<\/p><p>Lorenz studied <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Instinct\" title=\"Instinct\">instinctive behavior<\/a> in animals, especially in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Greylag_Goose\" title=\"Greylag Goose\" class=\"mw-redirect\">greylag geese<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jackdaw\" title=\"Jackdaw\" class=\"mw-redirect\">jackdaws<\/a>. Working with geese, he investigated the principle of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Imprinting_(psychology)\" title=\"Imprinting (psychology)\">imprinting<\/a>, the process by which some <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nidifugous\" title=\"Nidifugous\">nidifugous<\/a> birds (i.e. birds that leave their nest early), bond with the first moving object that they see within the first hours of hatching. Although Lorenz did not discover the topic, he became widely known for his descriptions of imprinting as an instinctive emotional bond. In 1936 he met Dutch biologist Nikolaas Tinbergen, and the two collaborated in developing ethology as a separate sub-discipline of biology.<\/p><p>Lorenz's work was interrupted by the onset of World War II and in 1941 he was recruited into the German army as a medic.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nobelprize.org_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Konrad_Lorenz#cite_note-Nobelprize.org-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In 1944 he was sent to the Eastern Front where he was captured and spent 4 years as a Soviet prisoner of war. After the war he regretted his membership of the Nazi party.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Konrad_Lorenz#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>He wrote numerous books, some of which, such as <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/King_Solomon%27s_Ring_(nonfiction)\" title=\"King Solomon's Ring (nonfiction)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">King Solomon's Ring<\/a><\/i>, <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/On_Aggression\" title=\"On Aggression\">On Aggression<\/a><\/i> and <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Man_Meets_Dog\" title=\"Man Meets Dog\">Man Meets Dog<\/a><\/i> became popular reading. His last work \"Here I Am - Where Are You?\" is a summary of his life's work and focuses on his famous studies of greylag geese.<\/p>","name":"Konrad Lorenz","place_of_birth":"Vienna, Austria","place_of_death":"Vienna, Austria","text":"Konrad Lorenz , Physiology or Medicine, 1973","year":1973.0}